DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("Numeric");


@unitsb = ('pounds', 'meters', 'hours', 'miles');
@unitsa = ('kilograms', 'feet', 'seconds', 'kilometers');

@left = ('K', 'F', 'S', 'K');
@right = (0.45, 3.28, 3600, 1.61);
@rightvar = ('P', 'M', 'H', 'M');

$index = random(0,3,1);

$a = $unitsa[$index];
$b = $unitsb[$index];
$l = $left[$index];
$r = $right[$index];
$rv = $rightvar[$index];


$n = random(3,20,1);
Context("LimitedNumeric");
$ans = Real($r*$n);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

A formula for converting [$b] into [$a] is [```[$l] = [$r][$rv]```] where [`[$rv]`] is a number of [$b], and [`[$l]`] is the corresponding number of [$a]. 

Use the formula to find the number of [$a] that corresponds to [@numberWord($n)@] [$b].

    [______________]{$ans} [$a] corresponds to [@numberWord($n)@] [$b].

END_PGML

##############################################

          
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

Since we are working with [@numberWord($n)@] [$b], we have that [`[$rv]=[$n]`]. We can substitute this into the formula:

    [`\begin{aligned}
       [$l] &= [$r][$rv]\\
            &= [$r]([$n])\\
            &= [$ans]
     \end{aligned}`]

So there are [$ans] [$a] in [@numberWord($n)@] [$b].


END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();


